qas.question: What is one of the two major highlands that stretch from the gulf of mexico to the Arctic ocean?
How far north do the Interior Highlands reach?
Which two nations are the central plains divided in?

plausible_answers.text: Laurentian Highlands, the Interior Plains and the Interior Highlands

qas.question: What is the name of the three highlands that stretched from the Gulf of Mexico to the Arctic Ocean?
The lower Mississippi and some of the Ohio basin are what type of region?
Originally trees covered all of what?
What Highland stop at the national boundary?

context: The <a0_0><b4_0>Laurentian Highlands<a0_0/>, the Interior Plains and the <b7_0>Interior Highlands<b7_0/><b4_0/> lie between the two coasts, stretching from the Gulf of Mexico northward, far beyond the national boundary, to the <a1_0>Arctic Ocean<a1_0/>. The central plains are divided by a hardly perceptible height of land into a <a2_0>Canadian and a United States<a2_0/> portion. It is from the United States side, that the great Mississippi system discharges southward to the <a3_0><b8_0>Gulf of Mexico<b8_0/><a3_0/>. The upper Mississippi and some of the Ohio basin is the <b5_0>semi-arid <b6_0>prairie<b5_0/> region<b6_0/>, with trees originally only along the watercourses. The uplands towards the Appalachians were included in the great eastern forested area, while the western part of the plains has so dry a climate that its native plant life is scanty, and in the south it is practically barren.
